<content>
    <section id="import-auto-id1167258898513">
      <title>Reverberation</title><para id="import-auto-id1167263738063">When sound is made in an enclosed space, echoes of the signal reflect of the room’s surfaces and form a <emphasis>reverberated signal</emphasis>, a superposition of the signal generated and delayed versions of itself with amplitude decay. These reverberations make listening unpleasant and can sometimes make a presentation unintelligible. The OEDK classroom suffers greatly from reverberations which are distracting when listening to recordings of presentations. </para><figure id="import-auto-id1167266833939"><title>Two Room Impulse Responses</title><media id="import-auto-id1167258292527" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/reverb.jpg" width="1012" height="249"/>
        </media>
      <caption>Echoes of the impulse can especially be seen in the echoic room, where the signal takes longer to decay.</caption></figure></section>
    <section id="import-auto-id1167266738668">
      <title>Reverberation Time</title>
