is the average of the Sabine Absorption coefficients of all the objects in the room.</para><para id="import-auto-id1167263692645">The Sabine absorption coefficient is a ratio of how much sound is absorbed or reflected off the surface of an object. This ratio changes based on the frequency of the sound. Rooms tend have more reverb at lower frequencies. </para>
      <para id="import-auto-id1167257232083">Empirically, the reverberation time of a room can be measured by recording the response of the room to a unit impulse or pink/white noise and seeing how long it takes for the sound to decay by 60 decibels. The measured reverberation times of the OEDK classroom, an acoustically desirable room, and a heavily echoic room are displayed below.</para><table id="import-auto-id1167273820828" summary="Reverberation Times in Three Rooms"><title>Measured Reverberation Times in 3 Rooms</title>
